article.description:
Barbara Farris scored a career-high 20 points
and Shameka Christon added 19 to lead the New York Liberty to a
93-83 victory over the Minnesota Lynx and their first two-game
winning streak of the season Saturday night.
article.headline: Liberty win back-to-back games first time this season
article.linkText: Liberty outlast Lynx for first win streak of season
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Barbara Farris scored a career-high 20 points and Shameka Christon added
19 to lead the Liberty to a 93-83 victory over the Minnesota Lynx
and their first two-game winning streak of the season Saturday
night.

"We looked at a lot of tape and finally realized that things
we've been doing have been taking us out of games," Farris said.
"We definitely have some momentum now. It's still a work in
progress, but this will feel good on the ride home."

Becky Hammon scored 16 points and Kelly Schumacher and Sherill
Baker each had 13 for New York (4-9).

Seimone Augustus had 29 to lead the Lynx (5-8), who have lost
four of five.

"I'd like to see more balance," said Minnesota coach Suzie
McConnell Serio, whose next leading scorer, Amber Jacobs, scored
all 11 of her points in the game's final 2 minutes. "We can't be
one-dimensional if we're going to be successful."

Leading 66-63 with just over 7 minutes to play, the Liberty went
on a 13-2 run to break the game open before Jacobs hit three
consecutive 3-pointers for the Lynx in the final 30 seconds.

New York led by as many as 15 in the opening quarter as Christon
hit three 3s and the Lynx struggled from the field. Minnesota made
just two of its first 11 shots, allowing the Liberty to lead 27-13
at the end of the first.

"We gained some confidence from what we did in the first
quarter," Hammon said. "Then we got a little rattled in the
second, so halftime was a nice break."

The Lynx rallied for a 36-35 advantage at the break, going on a
19-2 run and holding New York to just eight points in the second
quarter.

"You know we are good for one bad quarter a game," Liberty
coach Pat Coyle joked. "That's one of the things we are really
trying to eliminate."

Minnesota reserve Adrian Williams led all rebounders with 13 --
nine in the second quarter.

"What's not on the stats sheet is heart," Williams said. "We
should've had this game, but the New York team wanted it more. We
were a half-step late on everything."

Lynx forward Kristen Mann was helped from the court with a
broken nose in the final minute of the game after colliding with
teammate Nicole Ohlde while both were chasing the rebound of a
missed free throw by the Liberty's Loree Moore. McConnell Serio
said she hopes Mann can be fitted with a mask and play in the Lynx's
next game, Wednesday at Phoenix.
